    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-04-03T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-04-03T10:00:00-05:00" n="633"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d633">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">360D.115/3–2645: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        United States Representative in Finland</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hamilton</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-04-03T11:00:00-04:00"
                            >April 3, 1945—11 a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>51. Department’s general position is that in matters to which you refer, your
                    129, March 26, American nationals are entitled by treaty<note n="37"
                        xml:id="d633fn1">The treaty of friendship, commerce and consular rights
                        between Finland and the United States, signed at Washington February 13,
                        1934, and effective August 10, 1934; for text, see Department of State
                        Treaty Series No. 868, or 49 Stat. (pt. 2) 2659. With regard to the
                        negotiation of this treaty, see <ref target="frus1934v02#pg_134">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1934, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>, pp. 134</ref> ff.</note> to treatment no
                    less favorable than that accorded nationals of the most-favored-nation. They are
                    also entitled under the treaty to just compensation for any property that has
                    been or may be taken.</p>
                <p>Any statement left with the Foreign Office should be along these lines.<note
                        n="38" xml:id="d633fn2">In despatch 20, April 17, 1945, from Helsinki, the
                        United States Representative informed the Department that he had left a
                        memorandum at the Finnish Foreign Office setting forth this position
                        (360D.115/4–1745).</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stetttnius</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
